imir-putin","ctaButtonText":"START FREE TRIAL","ctaNewTab":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"5af00b06-7ecb-460a-82d7-3fa7ab7a9f11","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"As Putin’s constructed image approached that of a superhero, his style of rule changed too. The circle of real decision makers around Putin shrank, skewing toward people with a security services background. Putin has prided loyalty above all else, and many of the people around him are those he has known since his KGB days—or at least since the 1990s in St Petersburg.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"bb425ef5-9533-4d82-b17e-1fd63651ff03","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"These people almost never talk to journalists, making reliable information about the inner workings of the Kremlin hard to come by. Putin is a cloistered leader, who hardly ever uses the internet and mainly receives information in briefing notes handed to him in red folders by Kremlin aides. While he cultivates an image as a man of the people, he has come into contact with “real Russians” increasingly rarely, and usually in carefully scripted encounters.\u0026nbsp;","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"e635e6cc-163a-4508-a9db-392d371a1caf","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Even his then-wife Ludmila, in a rare 2005 interview to Russian newspapers, painted a picture of a taciturn and authoritarian master of the house. She said he could only be asked questions (never about work) when he came home late at night and drank a glass of kefir before bed. And Ludmila said she gave up cooking because her husband never praised her food. “He has put me to the test throughout our life together. I constantly feel that he is watching me and checking that I make the right decisions,” she said. The couple announced a divorce in 2013.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"fa996479-3398-4bce-904b-2e0fc7e42c0b","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Over the year